      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn this text, we will continue studying division from a sharing perspective and see how mathematics helps us explain what we observe in the universe.\n\nBefore understanding the sharings (divisions) that occurred in the universe’s earliest moments of \"life\" — and that we still use today — let us reflect on what we already know.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: What I Know About Dividing</b><br /><br />Suppose you have 10 fruits to share. If there is no one to share with, how many fruits will the others receive?<br /><br />If there is no one to share with, how many fruits will you have at the end?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Now let’s change the scenario and continue reflecting.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Simple Models</b><br /><br />Do you like questions that have only two possible answers, like \"yes\" or \"no\"?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_one",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Division by Zero\n\nLet’s return to an example we used when we first started counting (<htcite0>), which will help us answer Reflection 1.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3874d1e8-0f76-4432-9ee2-d8c8c9dccf53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Counting",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Left hand</td><td>Right hand</td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"img1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img1', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/Hand_Grape.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img id=\"img2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img2', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/RHand_Grape.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\">Figure 1: Representation of our hands. Source code available on the project's GitHub (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('240800f3-ede4-4deb-9d4e-915a3a03fa68'); return false;\">History Tracers Team, <htdate0>, Source code</a>)</td></tr></table></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The figure shows a person's two hands raised with all fingers extended, each pointing toward a fruit.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Sharing with no one\n\nFigure 1 shows a person holding a piece of fruit in each hand. Since this person is alone, they have no one to share the fruit with, so they end up keeping it all for themselves.\n\nIn this way, we can say that, for the process of sharing something to occur, there must be at least one other person with whom to share.\n\nOnce again, we will use the archaeological site of Caral, in Peru, the oldest known in the Americas (*Abya Yala*), as an example. In Table 1, we see an image of the site without any people present. This image was divided into 20 squares.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"ht-grid-container\"  style=\"background-image: url('images/Caral/CaralPiramideH1.jpg'); width: 100%; background-size: cover; background-position: center; background-repeat: no-repeat; margin: auto;\"><div>1</div><div>2</div><div>3</div><div>4</div><div>5</div><div>6</div><div>7</div><div>8</div><div>9</div><div>10</div><div>11</div><div>12</div><div>13</div><div>14</div><div>15</div><div>16</div><div>17</div><div>18</div><div>19</div><div>20</div></div></p><p class=\"desc\">Table 1: Pyramid H1 in the archaeological site of Cara (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('720f6dfd-4b86-4e07-a887-1010e1041a4d'); return false;\">Ruta Caral, <htdate0></a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('03c3743c-d268-4730-ba8e-d36b5c49e781'); return false;\">Youtube - Caral Perú Oficial, <htdate1></a>). Photo taken on <htdate2> during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1: Sharing</b><br /><br />1. Distribute one fruit to each person in the first 4 squares of the table.<br />2. Now, distribute one fruit to each person in squares 5 through 8.</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Since there are no people in the squares, it is not possible to distribute any fruit. However, notice that in both step 1 and step 2 of Practice 1, the final result was the same: no distribution occurred. In this scenario, we can express what Eric W. Weisstein wrote (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "fc6c2a04-8a51-4ea5-847d-9b71912828ea",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Division by Zero",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li>This conclusion is directly related to the fact that any value multiplied by zero is zero; in other words, there is no different outcome when multiplying by zero. As consequence, the division by zero is undefined.</li> </ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: Division and Multiplication</b><br /><br />Multiplying by zero means counting the empty set several times.<br /><br />When trying to distribute into emptiness, we saw that it cannot be done, since there is no one to receive.<br /><br />This raises the question: is there any relationship between multiplication and division (sharing)?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Universe\n\nWe do not have measurements from the very beginning of the universe. However, based on observations of the cosmic microwave background (CMB), recorded 380,000 years after its origin, we can propose models about what existed before (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\nCurrently, we understand that a great inflation occurred in the universe’s earliest moments, and afterward, energy was transformed into matter and light (<htcite3>). That is to say, at the beginning of the universe, there was also nothing with which to share energy. This may be our best example: counting or multiplying anything other than energy would equal zero. And dividing (sharing) this energy was imprecise, since matter as we know it did not yet exist.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "587cdba4-cefb-4df9-8514-2e50ccf88739",
                     "text": "Penzias, A. A., & Wilson, R. W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1965",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "28041ca0-f1c9-4ee3-bde1-bdd0693e3dca",
                     "text": "NASA",
                     "page": "Cosmic Microwave Background (CMB)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b9866acb-fde8-4fcb-b54d-ee7c481cc9e7",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Shared Origin",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "6dfe4b3b-8338-46ab-8149-2e073414907e",
                     "text": "NASA",
                     "page": "Cosmic History",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_one",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Dividing with Myself\n\nDividing with myself, or sharing something with myself, might seem strange. On the other hand, when we only think about situations like this, in which we are the main focus, it can say a lot about us.\n\n#### The Relationship Between Division and Multiplication\n\nWhen we talk about multiplication, we are adding repeated quantities by grouping them. In contrast, when we talk about dividing (sharing), our intention is to separate what is united. In this way, multiplication and division are connected, since both actions — grouping or splitting — act upon the same quantity. When the final result is obtained through multiplication (grouping), we can discover the initial state by sharing (dividing). On the other hand, after distributing part of a whole, we can regroup it again through multiplication.\n\n#### Writing Multiplication\n\nWe can understand mathematics as a way of summarizing what we observe in nature. For example, in Figure 1 we have the same fruit counted 10 times; expressed mathematically:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Understanding the Times Table (0 e 1)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>10</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>10</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 1 — Counting the same fruit represented mathematically.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Sharing with Mathematics\n\nNow we want to redistribute the total. To do this, we must remember Antoine Lavoisier’s discovery: matter is conserved (<htcite0>). This conservation is represented by the equals sign (=) in Formula 1. Based on this natural law, we understand that, in order to redistribute what is grouped, the following is necessary:\n- Write the total on one side of the equation and the way we represented it on the other.\n- Since matter is conserved, the quantities on both sides of the equation must also remain equivalent. In other words, when modifying one side of the equation, we must modify the other to preserve the equivalence observed in nature.\n\nTo know exactly what we are redistributing, let’s replace the numbers with names (variables):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "68227419-2430-4359-b902-f6cf87b8941d",
                     "text": "Holmes, F. L.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1985",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>Total Fruits</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>Fruits</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>Fingers</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 2 — Description of the quantities in Formula 1.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 4: To Move or Not to Move…</b><br /><br />Starting from the total number of fruits, how many fingers (groups) did we have containing the same number of fruits?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Reflection 4 takes us back to Formula 2. The total exists because we initially counted the same number of fruits per finger; mathematically, we performed the multiplication **Fruits × Fingers**. To know how many fingers (groups) there were, we need to redistribute (divide) all the fruits, that is, separate them again. Mathematically, we proceed as follows:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>Total Fruits</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Fruits</mi><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>Fruits</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>Fruits</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Fruits</mi><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 3 — Distributing fruits per group.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Formula 3 represents an intermediate step in our objective: isolating the **Fingers**. However, we still find the factor **Fruits** both in the numerator (upper part) and in the denominator (lower part) on the right-hand side of the equation. Observing that side, we notice a division that can be expressed as **Fruits ÷ Fruits**, whose result is 1. Let us recall that any number multiplied by 1 equals itself (<htcite0>; <htcite1>). In this way, we can simplify:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7a9c733b-ca13-40f5-8849-19012540b028",
                     "text": "Ernst, Dana.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Understanding the Multiplication Table (0 and 1)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>Total Fruits</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Fruits</mi><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>Fingers</mi> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>Total Fruits</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Fruits</mi><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mi>Fingers</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 4 — Expression of the number of fingers in terms of the total fruits and the fruits per finger.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Practicing\n\nFinally, we can answer Reflection 4 and discover how many fingers we had when there was only 1 fruit per finger. Taking **Total = 10** and **Fruits = 1**:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>10</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>10</mi> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>10</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>1</mi><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>10</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>1</mi><mrow> </mfrac> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>10</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>1</mi><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>10</mi> </math></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>10</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>1</mi><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mi>10</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 1 — Distributing the fruits across the fingers.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Analyzing the Result\n\nLet’s begin by recalling the 1 times table:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div id=\"mParent1\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: center;\"></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart3\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Graph 1 — Representation of the points in the 1 times table. Graph created with the <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a> library.</div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "From the 1 times table and Calculation 1, we can observe two important points for our study:\n- Multiplying any number by 1 results in the number itself.\n- Dividing any number by 1 also results in the number itself.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 2: Training</b><br /><br />1. Repeat the steps of Calculation 1.<br /><br />2. Now replace the 10 in Calculation 1 with 5, and redo the calculations to confirm that <b>5 ÷ 1 = 5</b>.</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
